default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultASCL has never opposed the idea of academy schools
default, and the majority of ASCL members now lead academies. 
defaultASCL members also lead
default the majority of colleges (FE and sixth f
defaultorm) and independents schools affiliated with HMC, GSA and the Society of Heads, the situations of which are in many ways similar t
defaulto
default that of academies.
default4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultASCL has always argued in favour of subsidiarity: decisions being made at the ‘lowest’ level possible co
defaultnsistent with efficient use of resources. This implies a greater degree of autonomy than schools have traditionally enjoyed, even after the introduction of local management of schools in the 1990s.
default5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMost ASCL members value extra freedom for them and their g
defaultovernors to make decisions in the interests of their students
default. In the view of ASCL they are better placed 
defaultthan either local or central government 
defaultto make such decisions. When policies are made remotely, and by officials however intelligent and well-meaning
default who do not have to operate them on a daily basis with real children, they often result in waste and poor outcomes.
default6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
