default14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhile the concept of academy schools has been welcomed by a majority of school leaders, there has been concern about 
defaulthow 
defaultthe change to academy status takes place. Those sc
defaulthools that freely chose to become academies, ‘converter academies’, 
defaultare generally content, many of those 
defaultschools 
defaultthat had, or felt they had, no choice are less so. 
default15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultASCL would strongly urge that decisions 
defaultabout change of school status 
defaultsho
defaultuld be taken by sc
defaulthool governing bodies
default, and not under duress. The drive to move schools to academy status has become a policy imperative, and there have been cases of the DfE effectively forcing schools to become academies. This has especially applied to schools in more challenging areas (‘con
defaultstrained schools’) that have failed to reach arbitrary floor targets. Other routes to improving schools in such situations have worked 
defaultwell 
defaultin some instances and 
defaultwhen favoured locally 
defaultshould be given more consideration.
default&#xa0;
default16
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome sponsors, especia
defaultlly when schools have had little or no choice of sponsor, have added no value while taking funds from the school budget, and in a few cases have imposed eccentric ideas of their own with little regard to educational thinking or educational values. There is
default a need to impose stricter conditions on what organisations can become sponsors. On the whole, the system has worked best when sponsors have been other educational institutions (other schools, colleges, universities).
default17
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultASCL would urge that school governing 
defaultbodies should decide whether on becoming an academy their school should have a sponsor, and choose the sponsor if there is to be one.
default18
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs the majority of secondary schools are now academies, and more are following suit
default,
default there is a question about the capacit
defaulty of the DfE and the EFA to support and fund them. It is generally accepted that it is not good practice to run significant numbers of local organisations directly from Whitehall. That raises a question of what types of organisation should be put in place 
default(either by government or by the schools themselves) to be a ‘middle tier’ between national government and individual academies.
default19
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a danger that these ch
defaultanges will effectively remove local authoritie
defaults from education
default, not replace them,
default and 
defaultso 
defaultactually
default centralise the system. The Secretary of State for 
defaultEducation 
defaultneeds to adopt a self-denying ordinance to prevent himself (and so far as possible his successors) from interference in decisions that should be better taken at lower levels.
default20
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are still some
default uncertainties about the regulations under which academies work. For example, the question of who is the employer of staff in a school should be clear, it should be the governing body, but some trades unions are continuing to take national action in such s
defaultchools in dispute with the Secretary of State.
default21
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe regulation
default, accountability and funding
default of academies and schools of other kinds (and so
default far as possible colleges) need
default to be brought into better alignment. There remain a number of anomalies.
