default22
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAgain 
defaultASCL does not oppose 
defaultchains 
defaultper se
default, and some are working well. However, some have imposed great restriction on local decision-making, making the governing body, head teacher and other leaders follow a ‘formula’
default,
default or imposing policies decided by the chain. T
defaulthis works against the principle of subsidiarity, leaves local leadership in some cases with less freedom than when 
defaultmaintain
defaulted by a local authority, and raises questions about the accountability of chains.
default23
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome chains have blocked local partnership working 
defaultby requiring their schools to partner only with other members of the chain, often at a distance. In some cases this has prevented potentially valuable local partnerships from forming at all.
default24
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOn the whole it is the smaller chains, and those with a more loca
defaultl focus, that are seen as of value by local school leaders of the academies that make them up. Those that are larger and have schools in widely separated locations are seen as more controlling, less supportive and less accountable.
default25
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a place for cha
defaultins of academies, but ASCL would not see them as the norm, or the answer to the ‘middle tier’ question.
default&#xa0;
default26
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAgain ASCL does not oppose the idea of free schools as such. At present
default,
default once a free school is established it becomes an academy like any 
defaultother. 
defaultThere are many issues, however, about the way that the free schools policy has been promoted, the way free schools have come into being, and the lack of planning or sufficiently effective regulation.
default27
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe key issue is how free schools are agreed. The
defaultre has been little attempt so far to consider the effect of setting up a free school in a locality on the schools that already serve it, and on the local education system as a whole. Where there is a shortage of places setting up a free school might well b
defaulte a sensible move, but where there is a surplus of places consideration should be given to diseconomies of scale. 
defaultI
defaultf the establishment of a free school leads to other schools closing there will be expensive public buildings surplus to requirement. And
default,
default 
defaultmos
defaultt importantly
default,
default 
defaultyoung people will certainly suffer while such a shaking out is taking place.
default28
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe free school policy has undermined attempts to plan school places. 
defaultIt is accepted that f
defaultor there to be parental choice there must be some surplus
default places, but these surplus places are expensive, and a charge upon the public purse. They therefore need to be as few as compatible with reasonable choice, but in some cases free schools have been agreed in areas that already have a 
defaultlarge 
defaultsurplus of places
default.
default29
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a great deal of resentment amongst school leaders of existing schools of all kinds about the favourable funding that free schools have received. Significant capital sums have been devoted to setting up new schools, when in some cases those nearb
defaulty have a longstanding unmet need for capital spending to make their buildings fit for purpose.
default30
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLikewise, revenue funding of free schools to planned numbers
default when their places have often not been filled has meant their pupils being funded at higher rates than in nearby schools struggling with very tight budgets. A period of austerity is not a good time for such an experiment.
default There is a need to quickly bring f
defaultree school funding into alignment with a fair funding formula that we hope to see for all publicly funded schools.
default31
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEven more than for academy sponsors, much greater ‘vetting’ of free school sponsors is required. There have already been instances of free sc
defaulthools being set up for reasons that have little to do with education by groups that not only lack educational expertise but make no effort to acquire any. Such schools will fail, and will damage children’s education and life chances while doing so.
default32
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome fr
defaultee schools will no doubt succeed, and join the family of schools in their area. Their leaders are also mostly ASCL members. Such schools will in a few years be little different
default from the academies around them.
